# Release Notes After Every Build

Whenever you **complete a new mobile build** (e.g. `flutter build appbundle`, `flutter build apk`, `flutter build ipa`) or **bump** `version` in `mobile/pubspec.yaml` for a release, **always end your response with release notes** — even if the user did not ask.

## When to include them

- After a successful release build command finishes
- After bumping version/build number for Play Store or TestFlight upload
- When the user asks for release notes (use the latest build version)

Do **not** skip release notes because the build ran in the background; check the build output and version, then write them.

## Format

Use **two blocks** — Google Play has separate fields:

### Short description (≤500 characters)

One or two sentences. Lead with the biggest user-visible change.

### Full release notes (bullets)

- 3–8 bullets, **user-facing** language (not commit jargon)
- Group: **New**, **Improved**, **Fixed** when helpful
- Mention platform only when relevant (e.g. "Android", "mobile web")
- Include **version + build** from `mobile/pubspec.yaml` (e.g. `1.0.9 (25)`)

## Style

- Plain language for listeners and artists
- No internal package names (`flutter_angle`, `WebView` only if users care)
- No "we refactored X" unless it affects users
- If the build is mostly web-only, say web updates deploy via the site; app notes cover only what shipped in the binary

## Example

**Short:** Improved 3D home hero on phones and fixed the bottom player blocking buttons.

**Full (1.0.9):**
- **New:** Animated butterfly hero now renders reliably on physical Android devices
- **Improved:** Frequency visualizer reacts more strongly to bass and beats
- **Fixed:** Bottom radio bar no longer blocks Sign out and chat on mobile web
